</li>
        </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sbuttons">       
       
				<div class="mr_social_sharing_wrapper">
				<!-- Social Sharing Toolkit v2.1.2 | http://www.active-bits.nl/support/social-sharing-toolkit/ --><span class="mr_social_sharing"><span style="display: inline-block; width: 55px; height: 62px; overflow: hidden;"><div class="fb-like" data-href="http://www.itinflections.com/dont-let-whaler-harpoon-companyor-career/" data-send="false" data-layout="box_count" data-width="55" data-show-faces="false"></div></span></span><span class="mr_social_sharing"><a href="https://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-count="vertical" data-url="http://www.itinflections.com/dont-let-whaler-harpoon-companyor-career/" data-text="Don’t Let a Whaler Harpoon Your Company…or Career"></a></span><span class="mr_social_sharing"><div class="g-plusone" data-size="tall" data-href="http://www.itinflections.com/dont-let-whaler-harpoon-companyor-career/"></div></span><span class="mr_social_sharing"><script type="IN/Share" data-url="http://www.itinflections.com/dont-let-whaler-harpoon-companyor-career/" data-counter="top"></script></span><span class="mr_social_sharing"><span class="stumble_vertical"><su:badge layout="5" location="http://www.itinflections.com/dont-let-whaler-harpoon-companyor-career/"></su:badge></span></span><span class="mr_social_sharing"><a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.itinflections.com%2Fdont-let-whaler-harpoon-companyor-career%2F&amp;media=&amp;description=Don%E2%80%99t+Let+a+Whaler+Harpoon+Your+Company%E2%80%A6or+Career" class="pin-it-button" count-layout="vertical"><img border="0" src="//assets.pinterest.com/images/PinExt.png" title="Pin It" /></a></span></div>        </div>
        <div class="contentsingle"><p>Businesses beware: The con is on. Again.</p>
<p>However, in the most recent phishing scheme to surface from hackerdom’s murky depths it’s not the rank-and-file that’s under attack. It’s those in the executive suite.</p>
<p>You may know it as ‘whaling,’ the sophisticated, effective and fast growing variant of the social engineering scheme known as ‘phishing,’ which we’ve <a href="http://www.itinflections.com/?s=phishing">covered extensively in these articles</a>.<br />
The latest ruse is so-called because hackers focus on landing the ‘biggest fish’ in any company, namely chief executives, chief financial officers and others with the authority to order or approve big-dollar disbursements from the company account.</p>
<p><strong>Sharpening the Weapon</strong></p>
<p>To snag their unwary victims, crooks first clandestinely access an executive’s email inbox or, posing as the exec, email internal gatekeepers from a phony domain that closely resembles the company’s legitimate domain. There may be some initial ‘probing,’ as hackers use phrases and language that mimics what they uncover in the executive’s inbox. They are patient and may analyze executive correspondence for weeks or even months before loosing their deadly dart.</p>
<p>These <a href="http://www.csoonline.com/article/3056677/security/10-whaling-emails-that-could-get-by-an-unsuspecting-ceo.html#slide11" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.csoonline.com/article/3056677/security/10-whaling-emails-that-could-get-by-an-unsuspecting-ceo.html#slide11', 'real-life whaling attempts, posted by CSO']);" >real-life whaling attempts, posted by CSO</a>, reveal some of the subtle typographical trickery cyber-cons have used in actual executive attacks. If you look closely, their apparent authenticity may also demonstrate why whaling is on the rise, and why recent incursions have been so effective.</p>
<p><strong>Why It Works</strong></p>
<p>Security firm Mimecast says that 55 percent of 500 IT professionals it recently surveyed reported a dramatic rise in whaling attacks, with more than 70 percent of attempts coming from hackers posing as CEO or CFO. More than 25 percent of attacks come from a <a href="http://www.scmagazine.com/ceo-sacked-after-aircraft-company-grounded-by-whaling-attack/article/499258/" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.scmagazine.com/ceo-sacked-after-aircraft-company-grounded-by-whaling-attack/article/499258/', 'Gmail address']);" >Gmail address</a>.</p>
<p>Of course, the scheme success is predicated on employees’ natural inclination to do whatever the big boss asks.</p>
<p>“Whaling is a pure social engineering hack targeting relationships between employees,” says Steve Malone, Mimecast’s director of security product management.</p>
<p><strong>Mounting Losses</strong></p>
<p>The FBI says that, internationally, whalers have swindled companies out of $2.3 billion over the past three years. In early 2016, top execs at an Austrian aircraft parts manufacturer lost $45.6 million dollars, as well as their jobs, to the scam. <a href="http://www.scmagazine.com/ceo-sacked-after-aircraft-company-grounded-by-whaling-attack/article/499258/" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.scmagazine.com/ceo-sacked-after-aircraft-company-grounded-by-whaling-attack/article/499258/', 'SC Magazine']);" >SC Magazine</a> and <a href="http://www.cio.com/article/3059621/security/whaling-emerges-as-major-cybersecurity-threat.html" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'outbound-article', 'http://www.cio.com/article/3059621/security/whaling-emerges-as-major-cybersecurity-threat.html', 'CIO.com']);" >CIO.com</a> detail other recent incidents, and goes into more depth on specific targeting techniques.</p>
<p><strong>Stay Afloat with Training</strong></p>
<p>In light of the recent whaling tsunami, and the escalation of phishing in general, Managed IT Service Providers (IT MSPs) like TeamLogicIT recommend stepping up education and awareness training for every person in your organization, including C-suite personnel.</p>
<p>Prudent precautions may include how to recognize the syntactical subtleties in email addresses, domain names, and even in senders’ grammar, spelling and punctuation, because English is often not the perpetrator’s primary language. Many companies have also implemented policies for confirming the approval and authorization of large, third-party payments.</p>
<p>Don’t let a slippery whaler sink your career or your company. For expert cybersecurity support, or assistance developing security training, policies or practices, contact TeamLogicIT today.</p>
</div>

        
